05791nam a22008175i 9783110553321DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105533217 a10.1515/97831105533212doi  a(DE-B1597)482964  a(OCoLC)1059284042  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aB755 7aREL0400302bisacsh00aScepticism and Anti-Scepticism in Medieval Jewish Philosophy and Thought /ced. by Racheli Haliva. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (VII, 179 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies and Texts in Scepticism ,x2568-9614 ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tBetween Philosophic Optimism and Fideistic Scepticism: An Overview of Medieval Jewish Philosophy -- tScepticism at the Service of Revelation? Preliminary Observations on Logic and Epistemology in Judah Halevi's Kuzari -- tThe Passion for Metaphysics in Maimonides' Thought -- tThe Purpose of the Guide of the Perplexed, Maimonides' Theory of Parables, and Sceptical versus Dogmatic Readings of the Guide -- tScepticism and Anti-Scepticism: The Case of Maimonides -- tThe Sceptical Exegesis of Maimonides and His Followers -- tThe Origin of the World - An Anti-Sceptical Approach in Medieval Jewish Averroism -- tThe Sex Life of a Metaphysical Sceptic: Platonic Themes in Gersonides' Commentary on Song of Songs -- tMaimonides, Crescas, and the Parable of the Castle -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe tension between reason and revelation has occupied Jewish philosophers for centuries, who were committed, on the one hand, to defending Judaism, and, on the other hand, to remaining loyal to philosophical principles. Maimonides is considered the most prominent Jewish religious philosopher, whose aim was to reconcile philosophy, in particular Aristotelian philosophy, with the fundamental principles of Judaism. But many other Jewish thinkers, before and after him, also struggled with this task, raising the question whether it is possible to attain this reconciliation. The connection between philosophy and religion was often not an obvious one. As a consequence, it could serve in some cases as grounds for supporting Maimonides' project, while in others it could lead to rejection.Scepticism and Anti septicism in Medieval Jewish Thought focuses on sceptical questions, methods, strategies, and approaches raised by Jewish thinkers in the Middle Ages. In a series of lectures, we examine the variety of attitudes presented by these thinkers, as well as the latest readings of contemporary scholars concerning those attitudes.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aJewish philosophy. 0aJudaismxDoctrines. 0aSkepticism. 4aCrescas. 4aMaimonides. 4aMittelalter. 4aSkeptizismus. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aJudah ha-Levi.  aMaimonides.  a Crescas.  a Jewish Averroism.  a Scepticism in the Middle Ages.1 aHaliva, Racheli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaliva, Racheli, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHalper, Yehuda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Warren Zev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKreisel, Howard, econtributo